context: "<b4_0>Alsatia<b4_0/>", the Latin form of <b5_0>Alsace's name<b5_0/>, has long ago entered the English language with the specialized meaning of "<a0_0>a lawless place" or "a place under no jurisdiction<a0_0/>" - since Alsace was conceived by English people to be such. It was used into the 20th century as a term for a <a1_0>ramshackle marketplace<a1_0/>, "protected by ancient custom and the independence of their patrons". As of <b6_0>2007<b6_0/>, the word is still in use among the <a2_0>English and <b3_0>Australian<b3_0/><a2_0/> judiciaries with the meaning of a place where the law cannot reach: "In setting up the <b7_0>Serious Organised Crime Agency<b7_0/>, the state has set out to create an Alsatia - a region of executive action free of judicial oversight," Lord Justice Sedley in UMBS v SOCA 2007.
